<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<exercise xml:id="exercises-power-sets" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Power sets
  </title>
  
  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the power set <m> \ps \of{ S } </m> of the set <m> S = \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } </m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  
  <answer>
    <p>
      The power set <m> \ps \of{ S } </m> of the set <m> S = \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } </m> is the set
      
      <md>
        \ps \of{ S } = \set{ \emptyset , \set{ 1 } , \set{ 2 } , \set{ 3 } , \set{ 1 , 2 } , \set{ 1 , 3 } , \set{ 2 , 3 } , \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } }
      </md>.
    </p>
  </answer>
  
  <solution>
    <p>
      Choosing a subset of the set <m> S = \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } </m> is equivalent to making a unique sequence of three binary choices of whether to include each element <m> 1 </m>, <m> 2 </m>, and <m> 3 </m>. We see that <m> S </m> has the following <m> 8 </m> subsets: <m> \emptyset </m>, <m> \set{ 1 } </m>, <m> \set{ 2 } </m>, <m> \set{ 3 } </m>, <m> \set{ 1 , 2 } </m>, <m> \set{ 1 , 3 } </m>, <m> \set{ 2 , 3 } </m>, and <m> \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } </m>. Therefore, the power set <m> \ps \of{ S } </m> of the set <m> S = \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } </m> is the set
      
      <md>
        \ps \of{ S } = \set{ \emptyset , \set{ 1 } , \set{ 2 } , \set{ 3 } , \set{ 1 , 2 } , \set{ 1 , 3 } , \set{ 2 , 3 } , \set{ 1 , 2 , 3 } }
      </md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>
